## Reason

The unseq compaction does not update the end time of the involved TsFileResource, even if the end time after unseq compaction is smaller than the end time before.
This case can be caused by deletion operation as the deleted data will be removed in a compaction.

Suppose a deletion (delete all data) is marked on TsFile 1 (time range: 0-100) and TsFile 2 (time range: 101-200).
On the 2nd write loop, all data will be written as unseq files, e.g., generating two unseq files, unseq file 3 (time range: 0-50), and unseq file 4 (time range: 51-150).

The merge process may run like this:
1. unseq file 3 is overlapped with tsfile 1. After merge, the time range of the ChunkMetadata in the new TsFile 1 is 0-50, while the time range in the tsfile resource is still 0-100.
2. Unseq file 4 is overlapped with tsfile 1 and 2 (check condition: according to the tsfile resource, rather than the chunkmetadatas, for performance considerison). First, we check the chunk metadata in (new) Tsfile 1, and find the last chunk metadata is 0-50, which is less than 51. Then, we check TsFile2, and merge the data into tsfile2. 
As a result, the time range in the new TsFile 1 is 0-50, while its tsfile resource reports the range as 0-100;
the time range in the new tsfile 2 is 51-150, while its tsfile resource reports the range as 101-200.

As the query process will select files according to the tsfile resource, the incorrect tsfile resource will cause some bug:
e.g., select * .... where time < 100, then all data in TsFile 2 looks lost.


## Solution
1. Maintain the correct start time and the end time of each involved devices in the merge process.
2. After finish writing a tsfile, update the start time and the end time in its tsfile resource: 
 - use putEndTime instead of updateEndTime
 - use putStartTime instead of updateStartTime
